title: Single- and Multiple-Ascending Dose, Safety, Tolerability, Pharmacokinetic, and Pharmacodynamic Study of LY3202626
description_brief: This study involves single and multiple doses of LY3202626 and will evaluate the effects of LY3202626 on the body. There will be 4 parts to this study. In Parts A and B, single increasing doses of LY3202626 will be given in capsule form. Part A will also include itraconazole given orally as a solution. Part A will last approximately 8-12 weeks. Part B will last approximately 5-6 weeks. In Parts C and D, participants will be dosed multiple days with the study drug. Part C will last approximately 11-14 weeks. Part D will last approximately 11-14 weeks and participants must have Alzheimer's Disease. Participants may only enroll in one part.

explanation_target: Reason: The protocol and title describe LY3202626, which is an oral small-molecule inhibitor of BACE1 (β-site amyloid precursor protein cleaving enzyme 1) developed to reduce production of amyloid-β — i.e., it targets Alzheimer’s pathology (disease modification). citeturn0search0turn0search2.

Act: Key trial details — single- and multiple-ascending oral doses in healthy volunteers and an AD cohort (Part D); drug reduces Aβ40/Aβ42 in plasma and CSF in dose-dependent fashion, consistent with BACE1 inhibition. These facts come from the Phase 1/2 reports and registry entry. citeturn0search4turn0search5turn0search2.

Reflect: Given LY3202626 is a BACE1 inhibitor (small molecule) designed to lower amyloid production rather than a biologic, cognitive enhancer, or symptomatic neuropsychiatric treatment, the correct category is 'disease-targeted small molecule'. Trial registries and publications confirm this classification. citeturn0search0turn0search2.
explanation_agent: Reason: LY3202626 is an orally available small-molecule inhibitor of BACE1 (β-site APP‑cleaving enzyme 1), which reduces production of amyloid-β peptides (Aβ) and therefore targets the amyloid pathway central to CADRO category A. citeturn0search4turn0search7

Act: Key extracted trial details — the intervention is LY3202626 (oral BACE1 inhibitor); clinical pharmacology reports show dose‑dependent reductions in plasma and CSF Aβ40/Aβ42 and CNS penetration in humans, consistent with BACE1 inhibition. These clinical and translational publications and registry summaries confirm the drug’s mechanism and development history. citeturn0search1turn0search7turn0search2

Reflect: Classification check — the intervention directly modulates amyloid production (upstream of plaque formation) rather than targeting tau, inflammation, synaptic receptors, or non‑therapeutic processes, so the most specific CADRO match is A) Amyloid beta. Note: development of LY3202626 was later discontinued by the sponsor, but that does not change the mechanistic classification. citeturn0search2turn0search6

Summary of web search results used as evidence: (1) J. Med. Chem. discovery/clinical development paper describing LY3202626 as a potent, CNS‑penetrant, low‑dose BACE1 inhibitor. citeturn0search4 (2) Clinical pharmacology/PD reports (including a published clinical study) showing robust CSF and plasma Aβ lowering in humans. citeturn0search7turn0search1 (3) Alzforum and industry reports summarizing the drug’s amyloid‑related target, trial activity, and later discontinuation of the BACE inhibitor arm. citeturn0search2turn0search6
